, well they were poor - going to these pawn shops you know. Oh - going to the - taking their clothes, taking - I've know people, it's true, when they've come home at Saturday and they've taken their clothes off, now it's true, it's not a lie, they took th
eir dirty clothes what they've taken off, not washed, their working clothes, and took 'em dirty to get their clothes out what they wanted for Saturday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5246476 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16455581\charrsid3816264 Would the pawnbroker take them in dirty?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2833882 LL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16455581\charrsid3816264 Yes. Well they were bun - they were bundled up proper
 - of course he'd have to examine them, see what they were in, the pawnbrokers would and they took 'em in exchange, happen with a bit of money what they had to pay towards getting their weekend clothes out so they could be dressed up Saturday and Sunday. 
W
ell then would go in at Monday morning and they'd get their dirty clothes back. That's gone on round about where we lived up Chorley Road and it's true. As true as you sit there, they were all their own you know. They were their own - their own clothes bu
t they had to do that 'fore they could get their clothes to wear at weekend to save trouble, you see.
